      "en":
          " \u003Ch2\u003EFirst: The Correct Meaning of “For the Male Is Like the Share of the Two Females”\u003C/h2\u003E  \u003Cp\u003E The structure of the phrase “For the male is like the share of the two females” does not indicate the combination of the two females’ shares into a single unit to be compared with the male’s share. Rather, according to grammatical structure and the semantic function of definiteness, it conveys comprehensiveness over the individuals of the numerical genus. The basic of the definite article “al-” on “the two females” transfers the word from an unspecified number to a genus inclusive of its individuals. In Arabic, this corresponds to what is known as the generic inclusive “al-,” which can be substituted with “every.” \u003C/p\u003E  \u003Cp\u003E Accordingly, the precise semantic estimation becomes: for the male is like the share of every female — that is, an individual correspondence, not a collective one. Had the intended meaning been that the male receives double the total of the two females’ shares, Arabic expression would have required explicit numerical duplication without definiteness, such as saying: for the male is double the share of two females — a construction different both in meaning and structure. \u003C/p\u003E  \u003Cp\u003E This understanding is reinforced by Qur’anic usage of the inclusive definite article elsewhere, where it refers to individuals rather than to an abstract collective unit. By analogy, defining “the two females” in the inheritance verse indicates inclusion of each female separately, not the merging of their two shares. Thus, the equivalence is between the male and each female individually, in harmony with both Arabic linguistic logic and Qur’anic discourse. \u003C/p\u003E  \u003Cp\u003E This meaning becomes even more precise when compared to the Qur’anic method of expressing numerical multiplication. It never expresses duplication through the word “like” (mithl), but reserves explicit terms such as “double,” “twofold,” “multiple,” or “multiplied.” This establishes methodologically that when the Qur’an intends the meaning of doubling, it states it numerically and does not employ the structure “like the share.” \u003C/p\u003E  \u003Cp\u003E Accordingly, interpreting the verse to mean “the male receives double the female” is not required by the text nor by Qur’anic Arabic logic. Rather, it results from neglecting the semantic function of the definite article. A disciplined linguistic reading instead leads to the meaning of individual equivalence: for the male is like the share of every female, not numerical duplication. \u003C/p\u003E  \u003Cp\u003E Accordingly, in the presence of one male and two females, the distribution among them is that each receives one third. \u003C/p\u003E  \u003Chr\u003E  \u003Ch2\u003ESecond: “And If She Is One, Then for Her Is the Half”\u003C/h2\u003E  \u003Cp\u003E The statement “And if she is one, then for her is the half” is a direct application of the same principle of equivalence established previously. Since the rule is that for the male is like the share of every female, individual equivalence requires that when only one party remains in the equation, that party receives the same portion as the corresponding side — namely, one half. \u003C/p\u003E  \u003Cp\u003E Thus, the half here is neither an independent ruling nor a numerical preference. Rather, it is the practical expression of individual equilibrium within the balance when the corresponding side disappears. This confirms that the Qur’anic distribution system is founded upon proportional equivalence, not numerical superiority. \u003C/p\u003E  \u003Cp\u003E In brief and without excessive elaboration: when a single daughter exists without a brother, she holds full entitlement within the domain of children. The entire estate devolves to her after deducting the share of the spouse (her parent) and the shares of the parents if present (her grandparents). Siblings (paternal uncles or aunts) have absolutely no right to participate in this case, because their entry into inheritance is strictly confined to the condition of kalālah, as will be clarified later. \u003C/p\u003E  \u003Chr\u003E  \u003Ch2\u003EThird: The Qur’an’s Deliberate Retention of the Term “Your Spouses”\u003C/h2\u003E  \u003Cp\u003E The text states: “And for you is half of what your spouses left,” and never says: what your women left, what your wives left, or what your widows left. This is a precise terminological choice. \u003C/p\u003E  \u003Cp\u003E Operationally, what does this mean? \u003C/p\u003E  \u003Cp\u003E It means that death ends life, but it does not annul the marital entity as a financial and social system. The Qur’an does not treat wealth as the “property of an individual who died,” but as the residual effect of a marital entity that existed as a unit of production and ownership. Thus it says: what your spouses left — meaning what the marital unit left behind after its dissolution by death. \u003C/p\u003E  \u003Cp\u003E This confirms that marriage in the Qur’an is not a passing emotional relationship nor a temporary social status, but an operational financial entity that contributes to producing wealth within the social structure. It is a dual unit inherent to the system, not merely a biological individual. Therefore, even after death, wealth remains attributed to the marital entity as an operative unit, not to an isolated individual. \u003C/p\u003E  \u003Cp\u003E For this reason, its position is advanced within the distribution system: its share is always separated before all other heirs and remains preserved in all inheritance cases — whether children exist, parents exist, or a condition of kalālah arises. This demonstrates the structural stability of its position within the Qur’anic financial system. \u003C/p\u003E  \u003Cp\u003E \u003Cb\u003EMethodological Formulation\u003C/b\u003E\u003Cbr\u003E The continued use of the term “spouses” in inheritance contexts after death indicates that the Qur’an attributes the estate to the marital entity as an economic unit whose effects persist, not to separate individuals. This confirms that marriage is an operational structure not erased by death; only its effects are redistributed. \u003C/p\u003E  \u003Chr\u003E  \u003Ch2\u003EFourth: The Precise Point of Issue — The Introduction of the Term “Women”\u003C/h2\u003E  \u003Cp\u003E The text states: “For the male is like the share of the two females; but if they are women above two, then for them are two-thirds of what was left.” Linguistically, it could have said: if they are more than that. Yet it deliberately shifted to “women.” This shift is operational, not stylistic. \u003C/p\u003E  \u003Cp\u003E \u003Cb\u003EA) Why was number alone insufficient? Why introduce the word “women”?\u003C/b\u003E\u003Cbr\u003E At the beginning of the verse, the measurement concerned a precise numerical case: one male in comparison to exactly two females — a comparison between specified individuals within a closed equation. The text then transitions to a broader equation not based on individuals, but on the ratio between the female side and the male side as complete counterparts in the balance. This transition cannot be expressed by “female” or “two females,” because the first is an individual unit and the second a specific numerical case. The system required an open numerical mass entering into proportion. Thus, the word “women” fulfills this structural role precisely. \u003C/p\u003E  \u003Cp\u003E \u003Cb\u003EB) The Operational Function of “Women”\u003C/b\u003E\u003Cbr\u003E In Qur’anic usage, “women” is not merely a bodily description but an organized collective entity with rights, effects, and economic and social regulation. Thus, “if they are women” does not merely mean numerical plurality, but the transformation of the female side into a complete familial mass within the balance. \u003C/p\u003E  \u003Cp\u003E \u003Cb\u003EC) The Direct Meaning Without Complication\u003C/b\u003E\u003Cbr\u003E First, the meaning of “above” must be understood as a transition threshold. “Above” is not mere counting but exceeding a transitional limit — a movement from a linear equation to a fixed ceiling. Hence “more than” was not used. Accordingly, “women above two” means: when the female side — as a complete party in the equation — exceeds the threshold of two in relation to the male side. The word does not establish a new ruling; it announces a shift from separate individuals to a proportional side within the balance. \u003C/p\u003E  \u003Cp\u003E \u003Cb\u003ED) Why Is “Above Two” Alone Insufficient?\u003C/b\u003E\u003Cbr\u003E Because it would leave the discourse within abstract counting. “Women above two” establishes that what exceeds is the female side itself as a recognized unit within equilibrium, not merely a numerical increase. \u003C/p\u003E  \u003Cp\u003E \u003Cb\u003EE) Conclusion\u003C/b\u003E\u003Cbr\u003E The use of the word “women” appears because the equation no longer measures individual numbers, but measures a complete side within the balance — the female side in relation to the male side. The system here does not operate upon one female or two females as numerical units, but transforms the measure directly into a mass of females confronting a mass of males, each considered a total side in the equation. There is no linguistic redundancy, social symbolism, or philosophical shift here, but a direct change in the measured variable within the system — from individual counting to balance between sides. Thus, the phrase “women above two” becomes operative when females form a numerical mass exceeding the initial equilibrium threshold (two in relation to the male), at which point the ceiling of two-thirds is activated. The word is neither superfluous nor ambiguous; it clearly signals the transition from individual measurement to collective proportional measurement. Accordingly, the equation operates upon the female side as a mass: if the ratio of females to males F/M ≤ 2, distribution moves progressively according to the inferred stages (half, then two-thirds). If the female mass exceeds this proportional limit, the ruling stabilizes at the ceiling of two-thirds, thereby preserving systemic equilibrium and preventing numerical imbalance. \u003C/p\u003E",
